614	Bone Broth - Stovetop		5 lbs beef bones\n1 large yellow onion\n4 carrots\n1 stalk of celery\n1 leek\n1 bunch parsley\n½ head garlic\n2 Tbsp black peppercorns\n2 dried bay leaves\n2 Tbsp apple cider vinegar	Clean all of the bone marrow out of the bones that you can. Marrow usually gives the broth a metallic taste when marrow is left in.\nArrange the bones across some racks set in rimmed baking sheets.\nDrizzle with a little oil to assist with browning then roast the bones in a 400°F oven for 40 minutes to 1 hour, or until the bones are deeply browned and haven’t given up much of their fat.\nPrep the veggies: quarter 1 whole onion, peel 4 carrots and cut them in half, and cut the stalk of celery in half. Lastly, thoroughly wash and trim the leeks so they fit in the pot.\nIn one big pot (as narrow and tall as you have), place the vegetables and bones in along with half a head of garlic, 2 Tbsp of peppercorns, and 2 dried bay leaves.\nFill the pot with water and add 2 Tbsp of apple cider vinegar then bring the water/broth to and keep at a bare simmer.\nIn the first hour of cooking, skim any and all scum that floats to the top of the broth.\nStir and then let simmer for 24-48hrs.\nAfter sitting for 24-48hrs, it is time to defat the broth by skimming all of the fat that has formed at the top.\nTake a small sample in a cup and place in the refrigerator for 1 hour to make sure it fully gels.\nFilter through a cheesecloth or coffee filter and enjoy.  You can also freeze it in portions and save for later.	bone-broth
615	Bone Broth - Pressure Cooker		5 lbs beef bones\n1 large yellow onion\n4 carrots\n1 stalk of celery\n1 leek\n1 bunch parsley\n½ head garlic\n2 Tbsp black peppercorns\n2 dried bay leaves\n1 Tbsp apple cider vinegar\n5-6 chicken feet	Clean all of the bone marrow out of the bones that you can. Marrow usually gives the broth a metallic taste when marrow is left in.\nArrange the bones across some racks set in rimmed baking sheets.\nDrizzle with a little oil to assist with browning then roast the bones in a 400°F oven for 40 minutes to 1 hour, or until the bones are deeply browned and haven’t given up much of their fat.\nPrep the veggies: quarter 1 whole onion, peel 4 carrots and cut them in half, and cut the stalk of celery in half. Lastly, thoroughly wash and trim the leeks so they fit in the pot.\nIn one big pot (as narrow and tall as you have), place the vegetables and bones in along with half a head of garlic, 2 Tbsp of peppercorns, and 2 dried bay leaves.\nTrim the claws off of 5-6 chicken feet - this helps with adding fat and gelatin to the broth.\nFill pressure cooker with water to the max capacity with 1 Tbsp of apple cider vinegar.\nSet to high pressure for 60 minutes - but you can go as long as 4 hours. Let the pressure release naturally.\nRemove all the solid ingredients and strain (preferably through a cheesecloth).\nPortion the broth into jars. Rapidly chill them in an ice bath and then refrigerate.	bone-broth
